# 🔥 Heap & Priority Queue

Many students think:

```text
Heap = Memory Heap
```

❌ Wrong.

Today we're talking about the **Heap Data Structure**, not heap memory.

---

# 1️⃣ Heap Data Structure

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose you have:

```text
10 50 20 40 30
```

And repeatedly need:

```text
Give me the largest element quickly.
```

---

# Normal Array

To find largest:

```text
10 50 20 40 30
```

Must check everything.

Time:

```text
O(n)
```

Slow.

---

# We Want

```text
Find largest quickly

Insert quickly

Delete quickly
```

This leads to:

# Heap

---

# Mental Model

Think of a company.

The CEO must always stay at the top.

Everyone else stays below.

Heap follows a similar hierarchy.

---

# What is a Heap?

A Heap is a special Binary Tree.

It follows:

### Max Heap Rule

```text
Parent ≥ Children
```

---

# Example

```text
         50
       /    \
      40     30
     /  \
    10  20
```

Check:

```text
50 > 40

50 > 30

40 > 10

40 > 20
```

Valid Max Heap ✅

---

# Why It Is Useful

Largest element is always at:

```text
Root
```

So finding largest becomes:

```text
O(1)
```

Very fast.

---

# Min Heap

Opposite rule.

### Min Heap Rule

```text
Parent ≤ Children
```

Example:

```text
         10
       /    \
      20     30
     / \
    40 50
```

Smallest element always at top.

---

# Mental Model

### Max Heap

```text
Boss on Top
```

Largest element stays at root.

---

### Min Heap

```text
Smallest on Top
```

---

# Heap Is NOT a BST

Very important interview point.

---

### BST Rule

```text
Left < Root < Right
```

---

### Heap Rule

```text
Parent > Children
```

No left-right ordering requirement.

---

# Example

Valid Max Heap:

```text
        50
       /  \
      20   40
```

Even though:

```text
40 > 20
```

Still valid.

Because heap only cares about:

```text
Parent vs Child
```

---

# Why Heap Is Usually Complete

Another interview question.

Heap is generally a:

# Complete Binary Tree

Meaning:

All levels filled except possibly last.

Last level filled left-to-right.

---

Example:

```text
        50
       /  \
      40   30
     /
    20
```

Valid.

---

Example:

```text
        50
       /  \
      40   30
          /
         20
```

Invalid Complete Tree.

---

# Why Complete?

Because it allows efficient storage in arrays.

---

# Array Representation

Heap:

```text
         50
       /    \
      40     30
     /  \
    10  20
```

Stored as:

```text
[50, 40, 30, 10, 20]
```

No pointers needed.

---

# Parent & Child Formula

For index:

```text
i
```

Parent:

```text
(i - 1) / 2
```

---

Left Child:

```text
2*i + 1
```

---

Right Child:

```text
2*i + 2
```

---

Interviewers sometimes ask this.

Understand, don't memorize blindly.

---

# Heap Operations

---

## Insert

Add element.

Then move it upward if needed.

Called:

# Heapify Up

---

Example

Insert:

```text
60
```

Heap:

```text
         50
       /    \
      40     30
```

Initially:

```text
         50
       /    \
      40     30
     /
    60
```

Violation:

```text
60 > 40
```

Swap.

Result:

```text
         50
       /    \
      60     30
     /
    40
```

Still violation:

```text
60 > 50
```

Swap again.

Final:

```text
         60
       /    \
      50     30
     /
    40
```

---

# Delete Max

Remove root.

Move last element to root.

Fix heap.

Called:

# Heapify Down

---

# Complexity

Insert:

```text
O(log n)
```

Delete:

```text
O(log n)
```

Get Max:

```text
O(1)
```

---

# How to Remember

```text
Heap

Top element always special.
```

